udy|title=Moderna Announces First Participant Dosed in NIH-led Phase 1 Study of mRNA Vaccine (mRNA-1273) Against Novel Coronavirus |date=16 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020|work=Moderna}}</ref>\n**COVID-19 pandemic: The [[Kentucky Derby]] is postponed until September 5, the first postponement since 1945.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wdrb.com/news/kentucky-derby-to-be-postponed-until-september-as-concerns-heighten/article_5e88ecce-6557-11ea-8c64-1bf69c1bc962.html|title=First Saturday in September: Pandemic delays Kentucky Derby to late summer|work=WDRB|date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n**COVID-19 pandemic: Online retail giant [[Amazon_(company)|Amazon]] announces that it will hire an extra 100,000 workers to cope with the surge in demand for online deliveries triggered by COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/16/tech/amazon-shipping-coronavirus/index.html|title=Amazon hiring 100,000 new distribution workers to keep up with online shopping surge caused by coronavirus|work=CNN|date=March 17, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[March 17]]\n**COVID-19 pandemic: [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in West Virginia|West Virginia]] becomes the [[U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic|50th state]] to have a confirmed a case of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/west-virginia-becomes-50th-us-state-to-confirm-coronavirus-case|work=Fox News|title=West Virginia becomes 50th US state to confirm coronavirus case|date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n**After 20 seasons, [[New England Patriots]] quarterback [[Tom Brady]] [[2020 NFL season|announces]] he will not re-sign with the team, instead selecting free agency.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001106575/article/tom-brady-announces-he-wont-return-to-patriots|work=National Football League|date=17 March 2020|title=Tom Brady announces he won't return to Patriots}}</ref>{{importance inline}}\n[[File:COVID-19 outbreak USA per capita cases map.svg|thumb|Confirmed COVID-19 cases per million inhabitants]]\n*[[March 18]]\n**COVID-19 pandemic: President Trump signs the [[Families First Coronavirus Response Act]] into law and announces he will invoke the [[Defense Production Act]] to improve U.S. medical resources<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/18/politics/trump-defense-production-act-coronavirus/index.html|title=Trump to invoke Defense Production Act to expand production of hospital masks and more|work=CNN|date=18 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> and that he directed the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development|Housing and Urban Development Department]] (HUD) to suspend evictions and foreclosures until the end of April.<ref>{{cite news|title=Trump orders HUD to suspend evictions and foreclosures|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/488227-trump-orders-hud-to-suspend-evictions-and-foreclosures|work=The Hill}}</ref> He also announces the temporary closure of the [[Canada\u2013United States border]]; cross-border trade will continue.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51949243|title=US-Canada border to close amid virus crisis|work=BBC|date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**COVID-19 pandemic: The Dow Jones closes down 6 percent, falling below 20,000 points, reportedly erasing nearly all of its Trump-era gains.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/18/business/stock-updates-march-18/|title=Stock trading halted for fourth time this month as S&P 500 drops 7%|work=Boston Globe|date=18 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**A 5.9{{M|?}} [[2020 Salt Lake City earthquake|earthquake]] hits [[Salt Lake City|Salt Lake City, Utah]].<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news |last1=Hanna |first1=Jason |last2=Toropin |first2=Konstantin |title=A 5.7 magnitude earthquake shakes Utah, knocking out power to thousands |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/18/us/utah-earthquake/index.html |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=CNN |publisher=Cable News Network |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n**Representative [[Tulsi Gabbard]] suspends her [[Tulsi Gabbard 2020 presidential campaign|presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2020/03/19/tulsi-gabbard-ends-presidential-campaign/2009989001/|title=Tulsi Gabbard ends presidential campaign, backs Joe Biden|work=[[USA Today]]|author1=Jason Lalljee|author2=Rebecca Morin|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[March 19]] &ndash; COVID-19 pandemic: The [[United States Department of Labor|Department of Labor]] reports that 281,000 Americans filed for [[Unemployment_in_the_United_States|unemployment]] in the last week, a 33 percent increase over the prior week and the biggest percentage increase since [[1992_in_the_United_States|1992]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/19/economy/unemployment-benefits-goldman-sachs/index.html|title=Goldman Sachs predicts 2.25 million Americans filed initial unemployment claims this week, the highest on record|website=CNN|date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[March 20]] &ndash; COVID-19 pandemic: [[Governor_of_New_York|New York Governor]] [[Andrew Cuomo]] orders staff at all \"non-essential\" businesses to remain at home as the number of coronavirus cases in the state exceeds 7,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51980671|title=New York orders all non-essential businesses to shut doors|website=BBC News|date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[March 21]] &ndash; COVID-19 pandemic: Biotech company [[Cepheid_Inc|Cepheid Inc]] reports that it has been granted FDA approval for a new rapid diagnostic test, able to detect COVID-19 in just 45 minutes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cepheid.mediaroom.com/2020-03-21-Cepheid-Receives-Emergency-Use-Authorization-from-FDA-for-Rapid-SARS-CoV-2-Test|title=Cepheid Receives Emergency Use Authorization from FDA for Rapid SARS-CoV-2 Test|website=Cepheid|date=March 21, 2020|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/21/politics/fda-coronavirus-test/index.html|title=FDA authorizes new test that could detect coronavirus in about 45 minutes|website=CNN|date=March 21, 2020|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[March 22]]\n**COVID-19 pandemic: President Trump says the [[United States National Guard|National Guard]] has been activated in California, Washington, and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)|New York]], thus far the most impacted states during the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-says-he-s-activated-national-guard-new-york-california-n1166211|title=Trump says he's activated National Guard in New York, California and Washington state|work=NBC News|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Washington National Guard]] clarifies that it was yet to be \"activated\", only declared available if needed.<ref>{{cite news|title=WA National Guard says it\u2019s not activated yet, despite Pres. Trump announcement|url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/wa-national-guard-says-its-not-activated-yet-despite-pres-trump-announcement/YKK2RABFS5FU3PBWPWEYY3NAZE/|work=KIRO 7|date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n**COVID-19 pandemic: The [[USNS Comfort (T-AH-20)|USNS ''Comfort'' (T-AH-20)]] [[hospital ship]] is announced to be deployed to New York. The [[USNS Mercy (T-AH-19)|USNS ''Mercy'' (T-AH-19)]] is to be deployed to Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/22/navy-hospital-ship-will-be-sent-to-new-york-to-help-battle-coronavirus/|title=Navy hospital ship will be sent to New York to help battle coronavirus|date=22 March 2020|work=New York Post}}</ref>\n**COVID-19 pandemic: [[Rand Paul]] (R-KY) is the first senator to test positive for [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kentucky|COVID-19]].<ref>https://twitter.com/RandPaul/status/1241780756617273345</ref>\n*[[March 23]] &ndash; Colorado becomes the 22nd state to abolish the [[Capital punishment in the United States|death penalty]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.axios.com/colorado-death-penalty-polis-abolish-e7c3207b-99d0-4ee9-9b49-9bde081aa4eb.html|title=Colorado governor signs bill abolishing death penalty|date=23 March 2020|work=Axios}}</ref>\n*[[March 24]]\n**COVID-19 pandemic: The Dow Jones jumps by over 2,100 points, or 11.3 percent\u2014its biggest one-day percentage gain since [[1933_in_the_United_States|1933]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/24/stock-market-live-updates-dow-futures-up-900-limit-up-hope-for-a-stimulus-deal.html|title=Stock market live updates: Dow soars 2,100 points, biggest jump in 80 years, stimulus close|website=CNBC|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n**COVID-19 pandemic: The U.S. [[box office]] records zero revenue [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema|for the first time ever]].<ref>{{cite news|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/mar/24/us-box-office-zero-revenue-first-time-ever-coronavirus-the-invisible-man|title=US box office records zero takings for first time ever as coronavirus crisis bites|date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**COVID-19 pandemic: [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nevada|Nevada]] governor [[Steve Sisolak]] bans the use of anti-[[malaria]] drugs for COVID-19 treatment, notably [[chloroquine]] and [[hydroxychloroquine]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2020/mar/24/sisolak-bars-malaria-drugs-for-coronavirus-patient/|title=Sisolak bars malaria drugs for coronavirus patients|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**COVID-19 pandemic: FBI agents kill a man in [[Belton, Missouri]] suspected of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Missouri#Timeline|plotting a bombing attack]] at a [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]] hospital believed to be treating COVID-19 patients.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/domestic-terrorist-allegedly-plotted-car-bomb-hospital-coronavirus/story?id=69803480|title=Domestic terror suspect allegedly plotted to use car bomb on hospital during coronavirus pandemic|work=ABC News|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n**A [[Gallup (company)|Gallup]] poll places President Trump's approval rating at 49 percent, his highest thus far.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/489285-gallup-trump-job-approval-rating-matches-all-time-high|work=The Hill|date=24 March 2020|title=Gallup: Trump job approval rating matches all-time high}}</ref> A separate [[The Hill (newspaper)|''Hill'']]-[[Harris Insights & Analytics|HarrisX]] poll places him at 50 percent, his highest since August [[2018 in the United States|2018]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/hilltv/what-americas-thinking/489340-poll-trump-lands-50-percent-approval-for-first-time-in-two|title=Poll: Trump approval rating hits 50 percent for first time in almost 2 years|work=The Hill|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[March 25]]\n**COVID-19 pandemic: Deaths from COVID-19 in the U.S. surpass 1,000 as the total number of cases reaches almost 69,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/26/coronavirus-live-updates-china-cases-spains-death-count-surpasses-china.html|title=Coronavirus live updates: US deaths soar past 1,000, according to Johns Hopkins University|website=CNBC|date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n**COVID-19 pandemic: The White House and the Senate agree to a [[Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act|$2 trillion stimulus package]]&ndash;the largest in U.S. history&ndash;to [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States#Economic impact|boost the economy]] amid the ongoing pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/25/politics/stimulus-senate-action-coronavirus/index.html|title=White House, Senate reach historic $2 trillion stimulus deal amid growing coronavirus fears|website=CNN|date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The Senate subsequently approves the negotiated bill (the CARES Act) in a 96\u20130 vote.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pramuk |first1=Jacob |title=Senate passes $2 trillion coronavirus stimulus package, sending it to the House |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/25/senate-passes-2-trillion-coronavirus-stimulus-package.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> Trump signs the bill into law on March 27 after a House [[Voice vote#United States|voice vote]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/27/house-passes-2-trillion-coronavirus-stimulus-bill-sends-it-to-trump.html|work=CNBC|date=27 March 2020|title=Trump signs $2 trillion coronavirus relief bill as the US tries to prevent economic devastation}}</ref>\n**COVID-19 pandemic: [[The Pentagon]] orders a 60-day halt on all overseas troop travel and movement as 227 U.S. troops have thus far tested positive for COVID-19. The withdrawal from Afghanistan will continue.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pentagon orders halt overseas movement for U.S. military over coronavirus|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|work=Reuters|url=https://news.trust.org/item/20200325203242-zgoc4}}</ref>\n*[[March 26]]\n**COVID-19 pandemic: The number of COVID-19 infections exceeds 82,000 &ndash; surpassing the numbers in China and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]] &ndash; meaning the U.S. now has more cases reported than any other country in the world.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus US live: US now has more cases than any other country \u2013 as it happened|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/live/2020/mar/26/coronavirus-us-live-house-vote-2tn-stimulus-package-bill-senate-news-updates-trump}}</ref>\n**COVID-19 pandemic: The Department of Labor reports that 3.28 million Americans filed for [[unemployment benefits]] in the last week, the largest increase in U.S. history. It supersedes the all-time high of 695,000 in October [[1982 in the United States|1982]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/26/weekly-jobless-claims.html|title=Jobless claims soar past 3 million to record as coronavirus sends Americans to the unemployment line|date=26 March 2020|work=CNBC}}</ref>\n**The Trump administration accuses Venezuelan President [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] and his government of [[Illegal drug trade|drug trafficking]] and [[narcoterrorism]] and offers a $15 million reward for information leading to his arrest.<ref>[https://www.infobae.com/america/venezuela/2020/03/26/estados-unidos-sancionara-al-regimen-de-nicolas-maduro-por-sus-vinculos-con-el-narcoterrorismo-internacional/ The United States accused Nicol\u00e1s Maduro of narco-terrorism and offered USD 15 million for data leading to his arrest] {{in lang|es}} Infobae, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n**The [[United States Space Force|Space Force]] launches its first satellite, an [[Advanced Extremely High Frequency|Advanced Extremely High Frequency (AEHF-6)]] military communications satellite that cost $1.4 billion.<ref>[https://www.space.com/why-space-force-launching-rockets-coronavirus-pandemic.html Here's why the Space Force just launched a rocket as the world fights the coronavirus pandemic] By Mike Wall, Space.com, 27 March 2020</ref>\n*[[March 29]] \u2013 U.S.-led coalition troops pull out of [[K-1 Air Base]] in Iraq, the third site left by coalition forces this month. At least $1.1 million of equipment are transferred to the Iraqis.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/us-led-coalition-pulls-3rd-113811539.html US-led forces pull out of 3rd Iraqi base this month] by SAMYA KULLAB, AP, 29 Mar 2020</ref>\n*[[March 31]]\n**COVID-19 pandemic: Three-quarters of the U.S. population are now under lockdown, with [[Maryland]], [[Virginia]], [[Arizona]] and [[Tennessee]] becoming the latest states to restrict movement. More than 163,000 cases of COVID-19 are now reported, as the death toll reaches 3,000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: Three out of four Americans under some form of lockdown|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-52103066}}</ref>\n**The [[Federal Communications Commission]] unanimously votes to mandate cell phone providers to implement [[STIR/SHAKEN]] by June 30, 2021 (for large carriers) or June 30, 2022 (for small carriers) to prevent [[robocall|robocallers]] who maliciously use [[caller ID spoofing]] to avoid being traced. <ref>[https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/31/fcc-mandates-strict-caller-id-authentication-to-beat-back-robocalls/ FCC mandates strict caller ID authentication to beat back robocalls] Tech Crunch, March 31, 2020</ref>\n\n===April===\n*[[April 1]] \u2013 Coal companies owned by billionaire West Virginia Governor [[Jim Justice]] agree to pay $% million for thousands of mine-safety violations. The companies operate in Alabama, Kentucky, Tennessee, Virginia, and West Virginia.<ref>[https://apnews.com/7a82d015133943b21f45117115bdbb2e West Virginia governor\u2019s coal companies to pay $5M in fines] AP, 1 Apr 2020</ref>\n\n== Predicted and scheduled events ==\n\n=== March ===\n*March 26 \u2013 [[Major League Baseball]] [[Opening Day]].<ref name=festivals/> Canceled\n*March 26\u201429 \u2013 ''[[NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA March Madness]]''.<ref name=sports> {{citation|website=88Teamwear|accessdate=Dec 22, 2019|title=2020 Sports Schedule |url=https://88teamwear.com/sports-calendar-2020/|date=September 28, 2019}}</ref> Canceled\n*March 27\u201429 \u2013 [[North Dakota Republican Party|North Dakota Republican convention]].<ref name=politics/> \n\n=== April ===\n*April 2\u20144 \u2013 Alaska Republican convention.<ref name=politics/>\n*April 4 \u2013 [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries]] in AK, HI, La, WY.<ref name=politics/>\n*April 5 \u2013 [[Palm Sunday]] (Western Christian)\n*April 7 \u2013 [[United States presidential primary|Wisconsin primaries]].<ref name=politics/>\n*April 9 \u2013 [[Passover|Passover (first day)]]\n* April 10 \u2013 [[Good Friday]] (Western)\n*April 16 \u2013 Passover (last day)\n*April 17 \u2013 [[Good Friday]] (Eastern)\n*April 23\n**[[Ramadan|Ramadan (first day)]] (Muslim holy month)\n**[[New Orleans Jazz & Heritage Festival]], part one.<ref name=festivals/>\n*April 26 \u2013 Puerto Rico Democratic primary.<ref name=politics/> Rescheduled from March 29\n*April 28 \u2013 [[New York State Democratic Committee|NY Democratic primary]], primaries in CT, DE, MD, PA, RI.<ref name=politics/>\n*April (''date undefined'') \u2013 Final Democratic Debate.<ref name=politics/>\n\n=== May ===\n*May 2 \u2013 [[2020 Kansas Democratic primary]].<ref name=politics/>\n*May 3 \u2013 New Orleans Jazz & Heritage Festival, part two.<ref name=festivals/>\n*May 5\n**[[Cinco de Mayo]]\n**[[2020 Indiana Democratic primary]] and Indiana Republican primary.<ref name=politics/>\n*May 7\u20149 \u2013 Wyoming Republican Convention.<ref name=politics/>\n* May 10 \u2013 [[Mother's Day (United States)]]\n*May 12 \u2013 [[2020 West Virginia Democratic primary]], WV Republican primary, OR primaries.<ref name=politics/>\n*May 15\u201417 \u2013 [[Electric Daisy Carnival]], Las Vegas, Nevada.<ref name=festivals/>\n*May 19\n**[[2020 Kentucky Democratic primary]] and KY Republican primary.<ref name=politics/>\n**[[2020 Georgia Democratic primary]].<ref name=politics/> Rescheduled from March 24\n*May 23 \u2013 [[Ramadan|Ramadan (last day)]] (Muslim holy month)\n* May 24 \u2013 [[Indianapolis 500]], Indianapolis, IN.\n* May 25 \u2013 [[Memorial Day (United States)]]\n*May 29 \u2013 [[Shavuot]] (Jewish holiday)\n*May 29\u201431 \u2013 [[Governors Ball Music Festival]], [[Randalls and Wards Islands|Randalls Island]], New York City, NY.<ref name=festivals/>\n*May 30 \u2013 Nevada State convention.<ref name=politics/>\n*May 31 \u2013 [[Pentecost]] (Christian holiday)\n*TBA \u2013 The [[United Methodist Church]] general conference in [[Minneapolis]] will vote on whether to split into two separate entities due to differences ove