{"title_page": "Baby I'm-a Want You (song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Baby I'm-a Want You\n| cover      = Baby_I'm-a_Want_You_-_Bread.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Bread (band)|Bread]]\n| album      = [[Baby I'm-a Want You]]\n| B-side     = Truckin'\n| released   = 23 October 1971\n| format     = 7\" (45 rpm)\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Soft rock]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Eder |first=Bruce |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/baby-im-a-want-you-mw0000318405 |title=Baby I'm-A Want You - Bread : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/5507/40_most_softsational_softrock_songs/franchises/list/|title=VH1\u2019s 40 Most Softsational Soft-Rock Songs|date=May 31, 2007|website=[[Stereogum]]|publisher=[[SpinMedia]]|access-date=July 31, 2016}}</ref>\n| length     = 2:25\n| label      = [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n| writer     = [[David Gates]]\n| producer   = David Gates\n| prev_title = Mother Freedom\n| prev_year  = 1971\n| next_title = [[Everything I Own]]\n| next_year  = 1972\n}}\n\n\"'''Baby I'm-a Want You'''\" is a popular song by the [[United States|American]] [[soft rock]] band [[Bread (band)|Bread]]. The [[single (music)|single]] was released in October 1971 (see [[1971 in music]]). It became the title track for the [[Baby I'm-a Want You|album of the same name]], released in January 1972. \n\nIt was one of Bread's highest-charting singles in both the U.S. and [[United Kingdom|UK]]. In the U.S., it reached No. 3 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart in November 1971, the third of Bread's four top-five hits (\"[[Make It with You]]\", No. 1 in 1970; \"[[If (Bread song)|If]]\", No. 4 earlier in 1971; and \"[[Everything I Own]]\", from the same album, No. 5 in 1972). \"Baby I'm-a Want You\" reached the top of the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|easy listening chart]] and rose to No. 14 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] in February 1972. \n\nIt was certified as a [[music recording sales certification|gold record]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]. As with virtually all of the band's well-known recordings, the song was both written and produced by the band's lead vocalist, [[David Gates]].\n\n==Chart history==\n{{col-begin|width=67%}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1971-72)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|U.S. [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1971)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|U.S. ([[Joel Whitburn]]'s ''Pop Annual'')<ref>{{cite book |last=Whitburn |first=Joel |date=1999 |title=Pop Annual |url= |location=Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin |publisher=Record Research Inc. |page= |isbn=0-89820-142-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|37\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1972)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Australia <ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Kent |authorlink= David Kent (historian) |title= [[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970-1992]] |publisher= Australian Chart Book |location= [[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives]], N.S.W. |year= 1993 |isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|57\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Notable cover versions==\n*[[The Lettermen]] covered it on their 1972 album ''[[Spin Away]]''.\n*[[Engelbert Humperdinck (singer)|Engelbert Humperdinck]] covered it on his 1972 album ''In Time''.\n*[[Wayne Newton ]] covered it on his 1972 album ''Daddy Don't You Walk So Fast''.\n*[[Aaron Neville]] released a cover as a single in 1972.<ref>https://www.discogs.com/Aaron-Neville-Baby-Im-A-Want-You-/master/1147932</ref>\n*[[Isaac Hayes]] and [[David Porter (musician)|David Porter]] covered the song in 1972 as the B-side of their single \"Ain't That Loving You (for More Reasons Than One)\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Isaac Hayes & David Porter \u2013 Ain't That Loving You (For More Reasons Than One) / Baby I'm-A Want You|url=https://www.discogs.com/Isaac-Hayes-David-Porter-Aint-That-Loving-You-For-More-Reasons-Than-One-Baby-Im-A-Want-You/release/7005166|website=Discogs|accessdate=24 September 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Ray, Goodman & Brown|The Moments]] recorded a soul version for their 1973 album ''My Thing''.\n*[[Shirley Bassey]] covered it on her 1973 album ''[[Never Never Never]]''.\n*[[John Holt (singer)|John Holt]] covered it on his 1973 compilation album ''1000 Volts of Holt''.\n*[[Stephanie Winslow]] covered it on her 1981 album ''Dakota''.\n*[[Conway Twitty ]] covered it on his 1985 album ''Chasin Rainbows''.\n*[[Jennifer Love Hewitt]] included a version on her 1995 album ''[[Let's Go Bang]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of number-one adult contemporary singles of 1971 (U.S.)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (1996). ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', 6th Edition (Billboard Publications)\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.discogs.com/release/1295994 Song info at discogs.com]\n*[https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/Mouldy%20Old%20Dough UK chart info at Official Charts Company]\n* {{MetroLyrics song|bread|baby-ima-want-you}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Bread (band)}}\n[[Category:1971 singles]]\n[[Category:1971 songs]]\n[[Category:Bread (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Adult Contemporary number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Elektra Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Gates]]\n[[Category:Pop ballads]]\n{{1970s-pop-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Baby I'm-a Want You\n| cover      = Baby_I'm-a_Want_You_-_Bread.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Bread (band)|Bread]]\n| album      = [[Baby I'm-a Want You]]\n| B-side     = Truckin'\n| released   = 23 October 1971\n| format     = 7\" (45 rpm)\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Soft rock]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Eder |first=Bruce |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/baby-im-a-want-you-mw0000318405 |title=Baby I'm-A Want You - Bread : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/5507/40_most_softsational_softrock_songs/franchises/list/|title=VH1\u2019s 40 Most Softsational Soft-Rock Songs|date=May 31, 2007|website=[[Stereogum]]|publisher=[[SpinMedia]]|access-date=July 31, 2016}}</ref>\n| length     = 2:25\n| label      = [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n| writer     = [[David Gates]]\n| producer   = David Gates\n| prev_title = Mother Freedom\n| prev_year  = 1971\n| next_title = [[Everything I Own]]\n| next_year  = 1972\n}}\n\n\"'''Baby I'm-a Want You'''\" is a popular song by the [[United States|American]] [[soft rock]] band [[Bread (band)|Bread]]. The [[single (music)|single]] was released in October 1971 (see [[1971 in music]]). It became the title track for the [[Baby I'm-a Want You|album of the same name]], released in January 1972. \n\nIt was one of Bread's highest-charting singles in both the U.S. and [[United Kingdom|UK]]. In the U.S., it reached #3 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart in November 1971, the third of Bread's four top-five hits (\"[[Make It with You]]\", #1 in 1970; \"[[If (Bread song)|If]]\", #4 earlier in 1971; and \"[[Everything I Own]]\", from the same album, #5 in 1972). \"Baby I'm-a Want You\" reached the top of the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|easy listening chart]] and rose to #14 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] in February 1972. \n\nIt was certified as a [[music recording sales certification|gold record]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]. As with virtually all of the band's well-known recordings, the song was both written and produced by the band's lead vocalist, [[David Gates]].\n\n==Chart history==\n{{col-begin|width=67%}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1971-72)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|U.S. [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1971)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|U.S. ([[Joel Whitburn]]'s ''Pop Annual'')<ref>{{cite book |last=Whitburn |first=Joel |date=1999 |title=Pop Annual |url= |location=Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin |publisher=Record Research Inc. |page= |isbn=0-89820-142-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|37\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1972)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Australia <ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Kent |authorlink= David Kent (historian) |title= [[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970-1992]] |publisher= Australian Chart Book |location= [[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives]], N.S.W. |year= 1993 |isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:ce